  },
  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "teacherTip",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "This module has been designed to use research-based practices in science education, particularly Ambitious Science Teaching. Questions on this page may appear to ask students about things with which they are unfamiliar or have had no prior experience as part of a science class. It is okay if student explanations are incomplete or incorrect. The goal is to get a foundation on which students can build their ideas. \n\nIn order to elicit students’ ideas and track them through the module, we suggest you use an off-line tool called a Summary Table. Summary Tables can be used individually by students to record their thinking as they progress toward an explanatory model of the phenomenon and guiding question: **What will Earth look like in 500 million years?** A Summary Table can also be used to record student ideas in a public place, such as a poster or a projected online document shared at the front of the room. (Please read these brief <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S-hG-ZKOmwEODJ0Q0HcsQ_sGH63JIL5sgq7MDDJiP9M/edit?usp=sharing\" target=\"_blank\">instructions on how to use Summary Tables</a>.) \n\nThroughout this online Teacher Edition, we will highlight those places where we suggest you stop and gather student ideas and record them on the Summary Table.",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

