    "windowShadeType": "teacherTip",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "By the end of this activity, your students should be building their understanding of the following key points:\n\n* Earth’s surface is moving. \n\n* This motion is constantly happening, happened in the past, and will continue in the future. \n\n* There are patterns in the presence of earthquakes and volcanoes on Earth, and these patterns overlap with one another. \n\n* Data from earthquakes, volcanoes, and GPS tracking can help us make predictions about how the pieces of Earth’s surface are moving.\n\nThe <a href=\"-ZKOmwEODJ0Q0HcsQ_sGH63JIL5sgq7MDDJiP9M/edit\" target=\"_blank\">Summary Table</a> is a great tool to track your whole class' changing thinking. Students should fill in the first row of the Summary Table with information they have gathered from Activity 1 to determine what patterns they saw in data they used (a claim) in column 1. In column 2, students should include evidence as to what is causing these patterns. In column 3, they should synthesize information from columns 1 and 2 to determine what information will help them answer the guiding question: **What will Earth look like in 500 million years?**\n\nStudents can work individually or in small groups to fill in their Summary Tables; however, bring the whole class together for a discussion on what should go into the Class Summary Table before moving on to Activity 2. \n\nYou can also track individual student work within the GEODE module with the **GEODE Teacher Dashboard** (<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1QsYPtZPClyQtWMnyCqktJL5G1xzOLq1rHLhwWj1PN1o/edit?usp=sharing\" target=\"_blank\">dashboard instructions</a>). The dashboard updates automatically as students move through the module and can be used during class to monitor student progress through each activity.",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

{
  "tipType": "windowShade",
  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "correct",
    "distractorsExplanation": "distractor",
    "exemplar": "exemplar",
    "teacherTip": "teacherTip",
    "teacherTipImageOverlay": ""
  },
  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "theoryAndBackground",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "The goal of this activity is to have students investigate the landforms and patterns of earthquakes and volcanoes associated with convergent boundaries. \n\nStudents will develop ideas about what must be happening along the boundary based on evidence from the real world and develop initial explanations for what is happening. Once students have made their hypotheses, they test their ideas using the modeling tool Tectonic Explorer (TE). \n\nThroughout the activity, we have included some “back pocket” or guiding questions you can ask students during class to help them productively engage with SE and TE as they investigate convergent boundaries. As students discover patterns in data, they can capture these claims and supporting evidence in their <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S-hG-ZKOmwEODJ0Q0HcsQ_sGH63JIL5sgq7MDDJiP9M/edit?usp=sharing\" target=\"_blank\">Summary Table</a> and then share their ideas in a whole class discussion at the end of the activity. \n\nThis activity helps students explore three types of convergent boundaries. It may be helpful to revisit the Summary Table after each case study to help students integrate the different types of convergent boundaries. \n\n",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

{
  "tipType": "windowShade",
  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "correct",
    "distractorsExplanation": "distractor",
    "exemplar": "exemplar",
    "teacherTip": "teacherTip",
    "teacherTipImageOverlay": ""
  },
  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "theoryAndBackground",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "This activity is designed around real-world case studies of convergent boundaries. The case studies exploring the formation of the Andes Mountains and the Aleutian Islands follow similar patterns. \n\nFirst, students look at the distinctive landforms by analyzing geographic profiles. Students then look at earthquake and volcano data associated with these landforms. \n\nAfter exploring the Andes and Aleutians, students  hypothesize about how plate interactions  can form areas like the Andes Mountains and the Aleutian Islands. Students then use Tectonic Explorer to test their hypotheses. \n\nThe case study later in the activity, exploring the formation of the Himalayan Mountains, requires students transfer what they have learned in the first two case studies to puzzle through a slightly more complex modeling of what occured in that location. (See the Theory and Background tip on page 5 of this activity.)\n \n**It is important to help students discover the connections between the real-world data and the motion of plates as they use the tools provided in the activity.** \n",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

