  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "teacherTip",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "At this point, students have engaged with data to help them understand what we see when oceanic and continental plate material come together. Using the last two questions, engage students in a discussion about what patterns they have noticed where two pieces of Earth are coming together. \n\nWhat evidence do they have to show that two plates are moving towards each other? For example, they may write that the presence of deepening earthquakes and volcanoes near a plate boundary means two plates are coming together. \n\nStudents should now add evidence to their <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S-hG-ZKOmwEODJ0Q0HcsQ_sGH63JIL5sgq7MDDJiP9M/edit\" target=\"_blank\">Summary Tables</a>. Revisit these ideas after completing this activity to help make students' changes in thinking transparent (to both you and your students).\n",
