    "correctExplanation": "",
    "distractorsExplanation": "",
    "exemplar": "In both the Andes and the Aleutians, volcanoes have formed on the piece of the Earth that is above the earthquakes. In both places, earthquakes get progressively deeper.\n\nThe profiles of the Andes and the Aleutians share some characteristics.\n\nThere is a deep trench in each of the profiles. About 200-400 km from the low point, there is a high point in both profiles.\n\nIn the Andes, the high points are very high. In the Aleutians, the high points are high enough to make islands in the ocean.",
        "teacherTip": "Here, students are building on their connections between the Andes and Aleutians, which are both convergent plate boundaries involving oceanic plate material that goes beneath another plate (subducts). \n\nCheck in with the Teacher Dashboard after the students answer this question. Compare their answers to this question with their answers to the question that asked them to predict what they would need to tell if two pieces of Earth's surface are moving towards each other. \n\nAre they making more connections?\n\nThis is a great place to ask students to think about to their answers to earlier questions.\n\nSee suggested discussion questions.",
