{
  "tipType": "windowShade",
  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "correct",
    "distractorsExplanation": "distractor",
    "exemplar": "exemplar",
    "teacherTip": "teacherTip",
    "teacherTipImageOverlay": ""
  },
  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "discussionPoints",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "Ask students to try to describe the ways that the two parts of Earth have similar patterns across the types of data, one data type at a time.\n\nStart with the profile, then the volcanoes, and then, finally, the earthquakes, including earthquake depth. \n\n**See if, as a class, you can generate a set of criteria that students can use to look for places where pieces are moving toward each other.**\n\nStart with small group discussions (3-5 students) so that students can discuss what they observed. This may help them communicate and clarify their understanding before moving into a larger class discussion.\n\nIt is important to have this discussion *__before__* students move on to the next page, where they will test their ideas with the Tectonic Explorer model.",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

{
  "tipType": "windowShade",
  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "correct",
    "distractorsExplanation": "distractor",
    "exemplar": "exemplar",
    "teacherTip": "teacherTip",
    "teacherTipImageOverlay": ""
  },
  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "theoryAndBackground",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "The phenomena that geoscientists investigate are extremely complex and can span a vast range of spatial and temporal scales. As a result, the creation of idealized models play a central role in the geosciences. \n\nTectonic Explorer is an idealized plate tectonics model. There are many different purposes for this type of model. It can be used to make predictions, or it can be used as an explanatory tool. In this activity, Tectonic Explorer is used for hypothesis testing. \n\nStudents will need to set up the conditions needed to account for the phenomena they have been exploring (Andes & Aleutians). \n\nMake sure your students pay attention to what they are setting up (locations of continents, application of forces on the plates, setting which plate goes over the other). They will need to connect what they did to set up the model with the outcomes of the model. Additionally, they will need their setup decisions to make connections between the model and the real-world case studies.\n",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

