    "distractorsExplanation": "",
    "exemplar": "The Tectonic Explorer model helps explain the geographic profile data:\n\nThe trench forms where one plate starts to go under another.\nThe mountains/volcanic islands form on the top plate.\n\nThe volcanoes are formed at a place above the underneath plate that is not right where it goes under, but when it is further down. Then the magma that forms above the underneath plate rises up to the surface to form the volcano. \n\nEarthquakes can occur when the plates are moving past each other. Earthquakes are shallow at the very edge of where the plates rubbing against each other, and then they get deeper. This is because the underneath plate is bending down and as it does, it cracks and breaks, resulting in earthquakes. You can see that the earthquakes make a downward pattern that is the shape of the the plate that goes underneath. ",
