  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "",
    "distractorsExplanation": "",
    "exemplar": "The plate interactions make earthquakes and volcanoes happen because of moving plates. The shallow earthquakes occur as the plates move away from each other and the crust cracks. \n\nThe geographic profile of the Atlantic Ocean shows that it is shallower in the middle and deeper on the edges (except for the edges that are right near the continents). It is the same pattern on either side of the mountain in the middle, which is a different pattern than the Andes (subduction). \n\nThe plate interactions help to explain this topography. The shallow part in the middle the location where the plates are moving apart. Something has to fill in the space that's created as the plates move away.\n",
