  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "theoryAndBackground",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "As students complete this page, it is important to stop and elicit student ideas on the question: **If two plate are converging, what is happening on the other side of the plates?** \n\nAfter students have completed this page, record student ideas on the <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S-hG-ZKOmwEODJ0Q0HcsQ_sGH63JIL5sgq7MDDJiP9M/edit\" target=\"_blank\">Summary Table</a>. (Use the Teacher Dashboard to see where your students are in the activity.) \n\nIt is important to make sure that students make the connection that **if there is convergence on one side of a plate there must be divergence on the other side of that same plate.**\n\nThis will help you set up the idea, later on, that there are transform boundaries that connect the different types of movement. \n\nBy considering all of the boundaries around a plate, students will be better able to consider multiple plate interactions at once. This is part of thinking about plate tectonics as a complex system. \n\n",
    "content2": "",
