{
  "tipType": "windowShade",
  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "correct",
    "distractorsExplanation": "distractor",
    "exemplar": "exemplar",
    "teacherTip": "teacherTip",
    "teacherTipImageOverlay": ""
  },
  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "discussionPoints",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "Goals for a class discussion include addressing what evidence is needed to identity a divergent boundary and what is happening at a divergent boundary. \n\n* What landforms are present at a divergent boundary? \n\n* How does the plate motion result in those landforms?\n\n* What events (earthquakes and volcanoes) happen at a divergent boundary?\n\n* How does the plate motion result in those events?\n\nStudents should record class consensus answers in their <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S-hG-ZKOmwEODJ0Q0HcsQ_sGH63JIL5sgq7MDDJiP9M/edit\" target=\"_blank\">Summary Tables</a>, adding to their mental models of how plate interactions form Earth's features. \n\nStudents should come to the conclusion that divergent boundaries occur where warm rock is rising through the mid-ocean ridge. From there, the rock cools to form new plate material. We can see evidence of this process in the presence of ridges and shallow earthquakes. ",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

{
  "tipType": "windowShade",
  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "correct",
    "distractorsExplanation": "distractor",
    "exemplar": "exemplar",
    "teacherTip": "teacherTip",
    "teacherTipImageOverlay": ""
  },
  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "theoryAndBackground",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "Traditionally, when learning plate tectonics, students are introduced to what happens at convergent boundaries, what happens at divergent boundaries, and what happens at transform boundaries through a series of similar diagrams. \n\nTransform boundaries, however, are messy, and patterns from data and landforms are actually more confusing than helpful. At transform boundaries, plates slip past each other horizontally along transform faults. \n\nIn the oceans, transform boundaries are associated with mid-ocean ridges and combine with divergent boundaries to form a zig-zag pattern on the seafloor. The mid-ocean ridges are considered divergent boundaries even though there is also horizontal movement. \n\nTransform faults also link different types of plate boundaries, such as in California where the San Andreas faults link the divergent boundary to the south to a convergent boundary in the north. \n\nIt is important to point out that in all cases of transform boundaries, the plates are moving parallel to each other. However, there are not obvious landform and earthquake patterns that connect both of these types of transform boundaries. As such, the treatment in this activity is different for transform boundaries as compared to convergent and divergent boundaries. \n",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

