    "exemplar": "The evidence that this place is a convergent boundary is that there are mountains. \n\nThe cross-section shows that a piece of a plate is going under (subducting beneath) another plate. This plate is going under because it has oceanic crust, and it is going under a piece of continental crust. There is a trench where the ocean plate goes under the continent plate.\n\nThe plate material going under pushes up mountains on the upper plate. \n\nOther evidence (that you can't see in this cross-section) is the formation of volcanoes. \n\nVolcanoes are formed as the subducting plate goes deeper and heats up. Water from the subducting plate is released and interacts with (catalyzes) the overlying mantle material causing it to melt. This magma rises to the surface to form volcanoes.",
