  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "theoryAndBackground",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "Mantle convection is extraordinarily difficult to visualize. Typically, convection is depicted as a two-dimensional set of circles in the mantle with arrows rising at a divergent boundary and sinking near a convergent boundary. \n\nBut Earth is not two-dimensional, and convection is understood to be more chaotic and complex then the simple drawings found in most textbooks. \n\nWe introduce a model of convection in a sphere to help students visualize a three-dimensional view of convection. This visualization is complex and students are **not** expected to fully understand it.\n\nRather, students should notice: \n\n* Warmer materials rise.\n* When the material reaches the surface, it spreads sideways.\n* When the material cools, it sinks.\n\nStudents should also notice that the convection is messy and not perfectly circular.\n\nHaving students consider how this visualization applies to the plate motion and landform features observed in Tectonic Explorer is really important. ",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

