{
  "tipType": "windowShade",
  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "correct",
    "distractorsExplanation": "distractor",
    "exemplar": "exemplar",
    "teacherTip": "teacherTip",
    "teacherTipImageOverlay": ""
  },
  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "theoryAndBackground",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "On this page students will be introduced to other important forces that scientists believe drive plate motion, both of which are based on the force of gravity working on parts of the plate. \n\nThe first of these, **slab pull**, acts on plates being subducted. Gravity pulls the plate downward into the mantle. You can think of this like what happens when part of a blanket is hanging off a bed and it is slowly pulled onto the floor by its own weight. \n\n\nThe second place that gravity plays a role is at mid-ocean ridges, where the crust is thinner and hotter. As the magma rises up from the mantle, it pushes up on the overlying plates, pushing them apart and creating a mountain. Gravity then causes the plates to slide down the high ridge that is formed, which continues to push the plates outward. This is called the **ridge push** force. \n\nRecent research has shown that plates with more of their edges being subducted are faster-moving plates, leading researchers to think that slab pull may be the major driving force. However, the science is not clear on whether convection, slab pull, or ridge push is the primary driving force in plate motion. \n\nOn the previous page, students explored convection. On this page, students will learn about slab pull and ridge push. \n",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

{
  "tipType": "questionWrapper",
  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "",
    "distractorsExplanation": "",
    "exemplar": "",
    "teacherTip": "Encourage your students to make connections between the representations in this video and the representations they have seen in Seismic Explorer and Tectonic Explorer. You may consider running this video on a projector in the front of the classroom.\n\n* What happens at a mid-ocean ridge? *(plates move away from each other as new plate material is created from upwelling magma)*\n* How is that related to the boundary types you saw in Seismic Explorer? *(mid-ocean ridges are divergent boundaries)*\n* How is the Tectonic Explorer representation of divergent boundaries similar to the representations in this video? *(ridge, thinner crust nearer the boundary, thicker crust away from the boundary, upwelling of magma at the boundary)*\n\n\n* What happens at the oldest edge of the ocean? *(denser oceanic crust sinks)*\n* Why do earthquakes occur as the oceanic plate subducts? *(cooler rock does not bend, so it fractures)*\n* How does this match the pattern of earthquakes that you saw in the cross-section in Seismic Explorer? *(pattern of earthquakes follows the shape of the subducting plate)*\n* How is the Tectonic Explorer representation of convergent boundaries similar to the representations in this video? *(subducting plate making a trench, formation of volcanoes on non-subducting plate)*\n\n\n\n",
    "teacherTipImageOverlay": ""
