  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "discussionPoints",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "For a long time scientists thought that convection was the only force causing plates to move. Scientists now have evidence that convection, slab pull, and ridge push all cause plate movement. \n\nUsing what you’ve learned in this module, discuss the following: \n\n* How do you think convection, slab pull, and ridge push work together?\n\n* Why are scientists still unsure about what causes plate motion?\n\n* What other evidence might help them be more certain?\n\n**Make sure to record student ideas in the class <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S-hG-ZKOmwEODJ0Q0HcsQ_sGH63JIL5sgq7MDDJiP9M/edit\" target=\"_blank\">Summary Table</a> in row 4.** Students should place claims about patterns they observed in column 1. In column 2, they should list the causes or evidence that supports their claims. In column 3, students should determine how that information helps them answer the guiding question: “What will the Earth look like in 500 million years?”\n",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
