  },
  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "theoryAndBackground",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "The goal of this activity is to have students work like geoscientists and apply what they have learned about Earth’s plate system to puzzle out different case studies on Earth. \n\nStudents begin this activity investigating real-world data about *the current rate of plate motion and direction along plate boundaries on Earth*. They consider *how the Appalachian Mountains formed* when it doesn’t appear to be near any plate boundaries, and they attempt to *predict what Earth might look like in the future* based on their understanding of plate motion and plate tectonics.\n\nFor each of the challenges students face in this activity, they should consider that major geologic landforms, such as mountains, trenches, and oceans, and tectonic events, like volcanoes and earthquakes, occurring in bands are important clues both for figuring out what happened in Earth’s history and for predicting what might happen well into the future.\n\n",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
