{
  "tipType": "questionWrapper",
  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "",
    "distractorsExplanation": "",
    "exemplar": "The nearest current plate boundary (in the mid-Atlantic) is a divergent boundary, meaning that the plates are moving away from each other. This means that, in the past, North America was closer to Europe and Africa than it is today (Europe and Africa being on the other side of the divergent boundary).\n\nThe Appalachians formed as two plates came together. The mountains would have started with volcanic islands, as the oceanic crust between the continents (in this case, North America, Europe, and Africa) subducted. \n\nWhen all of the oceanic crust had subducted, closing the ocean, the continents came together, pushing up very tall mountains. The Appalachian Mountains at that point were much like the Himalayan Mountains today. \n\nThen the plates began to move away from each other. This was the start of the current plate boundary (a divergent boundary in the middle of the Atlantic Ocean). The continents began to separate from each other, leaving evidence of the mountain range on both sides of the boundary. (In Europe and Africa, you can see evidence of mountains. These mountains were once connected with the Appalachians.) \n\nAs the plates continued to diverge, a new ocean (the Atlantic Ocean) was formed. The ocean was initially shallow (like today's Red Sea). Over time, as the plates continued to diverge, the ocean became deeper. Today, the divergent boundary is marked by an underwater mountain range, with the deepest sections of ocean on either side of the central boundary.\n\nOver time, the Appalachian Mountains (and the corresponding mountains in Europe and Africa) weathered away, losing much of their height. This weathering is always happening, but without the uplifting force of the convergent boundary to counteract the weathering forces, the mountains continue to shrink today.\n",
    "teacherTip": "Remind students to look for what is NOT there, rather than what is (e.g. volcanoes and earthquakes).\n\nAsk students where the closest plate boundary is located today. What type of boundary is it? What does that mean for where North America was in Earth’s past?\n\nWhat features are on the other side of the current plate boundary? Do these features help to explain what happened in the past?",
    "teacherTipImageOverlay": ""
  },
