    "distractorsExplanation": "",
    "exemplar": "The Red Sea formed as the African plate and the Arabian plate diverged. \n\nThe geographic profile shows that the Red Sea has a symmetric profile. It slopes down at the same rate from the African side as from the Arabian side. It appears that there is a small ridge in the middle of the Red Sea. It is not deepest in the middle.\n\nSeismic Explorer data show that there is a divergent boundary that coincides with the ridge in the center of the Red Sea. There is no plate motion data provided in Seismic Explorer.\n\nThe earthquakes are shallow and located mainly along the center ridge in the Red Sea. There are some volcanoes at the southern end of the Red Sea, some at the center, where the spreading ridge is located.\n\nAll of these data (earthquake, volcano, and landform) are consistent with the divergent plate boundary marking in Seismic Explorer. ",
    "teacherTip": "",
