  "windowShade": {
    "windowShadeType": "theoryAndBackground",
    "layout": "mediaLeft",
    "content": "At the end of this final activity in the GEODE module sequence, your students should understand how interacting plates leave clues about what happened in Earth’s past. They should also understand how these clues provide evidence for scientists to reason about what is happening on Earth in the present and even make predictions about how Earth may change in the future.\n\nWhen students have completed this page, return to the <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S-hG-ZKOmwEODJ0Q0HcsQ_sGH63JIL5sgq7MDDJiP9M/edit\" target=\"_blank\">Summary Table</a> and elicit students’ ideas about how Earth’s plate motions have changed over time. By this point, students should understand that:\n\n* Plate interactions have been acting the same way over Earth’s history and will continue to interact in the same ways.\n\n* Plate interactions can be used to explain the distribution of landforms and patterns of geologic events on Earth.\n\n* Although geoscientists can look backwards and forwards in time, Earth is very complex.  There is no way to predict what will happen with complete certainty.",
    "content2": "",
    "mediaType": "none",
    "mediaCaption": "Last, First. \"Title of Work.\" Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.",
    "mediaURL": ""
  }
}

{
  "tipType": "questionWrapper",
  "questionWrapper": {
    "correctExplanation": "\n",
    "distractorsExplanation": "",
    "exemplar": "In 500 million years, I expect that the continents of Africa and South America will be farther apart and that the Atlantic Ocean would be even wider. This is all based on the information that I have about how the continents are moving today. \n\nThe shapes and sizes of the continents would remain the same. Africa would be farther east than it is today, and South America would be farther west. \n\n500 million years into the future is a very long time, though, so the motion of the plates could change. It's possible that the Atlantic Ocean will start to close again by that time. This would mean that Africa and South America might be near their current locations or even closer together than they are today.\n\nIf the Atlantic Ocean starts to close, that means that the oceanic crust part of a plate would start to subduct. This would result in the creation of large mountains, like the Andes, with many volcanoes, along the coast of one of the continents. ",
    "teacherTip": "",
    "teacherTipImageOverlay": ""
